---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import RelatedResearch from '../../../components/RelatedResearch.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Methodology: Plastic Surgery Patient Age Dataset | Ranking Atlas"
  description="How Ranking Atlas computed mean patient age from ASPS bracket data. Source selection, midpoints, 2021 interpolation, coverage notes, and known limitations for both the Modern (2018–2024) and Historical (2001–2024) products."
>
<div class="bg-white">
  <section class="pt-20 md:pt-28 pb-16 border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-brand font-medium mb-3">Methodology</div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-[1.1] mb-6">
        The Plastic Surgery Patient Age Dataset: Methodology
      </h1>
      <p class="text-body text-[19px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
        Compiled by Ranking Atlas, April 2026. This document covers both data products: the Modern series (ASPS, 2018–2024) and the Historical Atlas (ASAPS + ASPS, 2001–2024). The split is deliberate, and the reasons are explained below.
      </p>
      <a href="/resources/plastic-surgery-patient-age" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-brand hover:text-brand-dark transition-colors font-medium">
        ← Back to the full report
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-16 border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 space-y-10">

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">The Two Products</h2>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-2">Product 1 (Primary): The Modern Plastic Surgery Patient: Age, 2018–2024</h3>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-3">
          <strong>Source:</strong> American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) only.<br />
          <strong>Years:</strong> 2018, 2020, 2021 (interpolated), 2022, 2023, 2024.<br />
          <strong>Procedures:</strong> 14, with one mean-age value per procedure-year.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
          This is the credible product. One reporting body, one bracket structure, one survey methodology. Apparent changes between years are far more likely to reflect real demographic shifts than measurement artifacts.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-2">Product 2 (Supporting): The Plastic Surgery Patient Age Atlas, 2001–2024</h3>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-3">
          <strong>Sources:</strong> ASAPS (Aesthetic Society) for 2001–2017 and 2019; ASPS for 2018, 2020, 2022, 2023, 2024; interpolated for 2021.<br />
          <strong>Years:</strong> 24 consecutive years, 2001 through 2024.<br />
          <strong>Procedures:</strong> 14, with mixed coverage (some procedures lack early-year data).
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">
          This is the historical context product. It exists to answer the question "what does the long-arc look like?" but it cannot be used to make confident year-to-year claims because of methodological discontinuities at 2018 and 2019.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Why The Split</h2>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-3">
          A defensible research asset needs three things: a single coherent dataset, a clear narrative, and the ability to answer follow-up questions without methodology reversals.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">
          The 2018–2024 ASPS dataset gives all three. The 24-year reconstruction gives long-arc context but makes the central narrative harder to defend if a reader asks "what changed in 2018?" The split lets the strong, narrow story lead, with the long history as supporting documentation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Mean Age Computation</h2>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
          For each (procedure, year), the source report provides patient counts in age brackets. We apply each bracket's arithmetic midpoint as the assumed within-bracket mean and compute a count-weighted average:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-[#F8F7FA] rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 px-6 py-4 font-mono text-sm text-ink mb-4">
          mean_age = &Sigma;(count<sub>i</sub> &times; midpoint<sub>i</sub>) / &Sigma;(count<sub>i</sub>)
        </div>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">
          This is a standard demographic technique for working with bracketed count data.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Bracket Midpoints</h2>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">ASPS (Product 1, all 2018+ years)</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left bg-white rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8 bg-[#F8F7FA]">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Bracket</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink text-right">Midpoint</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/6">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">13–19</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">17.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">20–29</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">24.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">30–39</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">34.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">40–54</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">47.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">55+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">65.0</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-body text-[16px] leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Where ASPS reports separate 55–69 and 70+ counts, they are summed and treated as a combined 55+ bracket with midpoint 65.0.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">ASAPS Pre-2019 (Product 2 supporting data, 2001–2017)</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left bg-white rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8 bg-[#F8F7FA]">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Bracket</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink text-right">Midpoint</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/6">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">18 and under</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">16.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">19–34</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">26.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">35–50</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">42.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">51–64</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">57.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">65+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">72.0</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink mb-3">ASAPS 2019 Only</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left bg-white rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8 bg-[#F8F7FA]">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Bracket</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink text-right">Midpoint</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/6">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">17 and under</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">14.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">18–34</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">26.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">35–50</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">42.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">51–64</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">57.5</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3 text-body">65+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-right text-body">72.0</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Why The Modern Dataset Is More Credible</h2>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-4">
          Two methodological events make 2001–2017 ASAPS data and 2018+ ASPS data not directly comparable:
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-3">
          <strong>1. Different age brackets.</strong> ASAPS pre-2019 used a 19–34 lump that ASPS splits into 20–29 and 30–39. The ASPS structure exposes finer age resolution and pulls weighted means in the direction of whichever sub-bracket is heaviest, typically 20–29 for elective procedures. This single bracket-design difference produces apparent age shifts of 1–3 years that reflect measurement, not demographics.
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">
          <strong>2. Different sampling frames.</strong> ASAPS pre-2018 surveyed plastic surgeons, dermatologists, and otolaryngologists in a multi-specialty sample. ASAPS 2019 narrowed to plastic surgeons only. ASPS surveys ASPS members and a wider physician network including non-ASPS providers. The compositions are different, and they capture different patient pools.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Coverage Notes: Product 1 (Modern)</h2>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm text-left bg-white rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-[#0A0F1E]/8 bg-[#F8F7FA]">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Procedure</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Coverage</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-ink">Note</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/6 text-body">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Breast augmentation</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Breast lift</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Breast reduction</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2020–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Not separately broken out in ASPS 2018</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Gynecomastia</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Abdominoplasty</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Liposuction</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Eyelid surgery</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Facelift</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Forehead lift</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Neck lift</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2020–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Not separately broken out in ASPS 2018</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Rhinoplasty</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Otoplasty</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3"></td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Botulinum toxin</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2023 and 2024 apply 2022 bracket distribution; totals match published ASPS figures</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">HA fillers</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2018–2024</td><td class="px-4 py-3">2023 and 2024 apply 2022 bracket distribution; totals match published ASPS figures</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Years With No Data</h2>
        <ul class="space-y-3 text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] list-disc pl-5">
          <li><strong>2000:</strong> ASAPS skipped publication of a 2000 report.</li>
          <li><strong>2018 ASAPS:</strong> ASAPS did not publish a 2018 report; ASPS 2018 is used instead.</li>
          <li><strong>2021:</strong> Neither organization published a standalone 2021 dataset. ASPS combined 2020 and 2021 into one report. The 2021 value is the linear midpoint of the 2020 and 2022 ASPS values. On the chart, interpolated points use an open marker.</li>
          <li><strong>2025:</strong> The ASPS 2025 report covering 2025 procedures is expected mid-2026.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Sources</h2>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7] mb-3">
          <strong>ASPS (primary):</strong> Plastic Surgery Statistics Report, 2018, 2020, 2022, 2023, and 2024 editions.<br />
          Index: <a href="https://www.plasticsurgery.org/news/plastic-surgery-statistics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">plasticsurgery.org/news/plastic-surgery-statistics</a>
        </p>
        <p class="text-body text-[17px] leading-[1.7]">
          <strong>ASAPS (supporting):</strong> Cosmetic Surgery National Data Bank, 2001–2017 and 2019 editions.<br />
          Index: <a href="https://www.theaestheticsociety.org/media/procedural-statistics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">theaestheticsociety.org/media/procedural-statistics</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-4">Citation</h2>
        <div class="bg-[#F8F7FA] rounded-xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 px-6 py-5 space-y-3 text-body text-[16px] leading-[1.7]">
          <p>Ranking Atlas (2026). <em>The Modern Plastic Surgery Patient: Age, 2018–2024.</em> Compiled from the ASPS Plastic Surgery Statistics Report. https://ranking-atlas.com/resources/plastic-surgery-patient-age/</p>
          <p>Ranking Atlas (2026). <em>The Plastic Surgery Patient Age Atlas, 2001–2024.</em> Compiled from the ASAPS Cosmetic Surgery National Data Bank (2001–2019) and the ASPS Plastic Surgery Statistics Report (2018, 2020, 2022–2024).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <RelatedResearch
    items={[
      {
        title: "How Old Are Plastic Surgery Patients In The US: Mean Age By Procedure 2018-2024",
        description: "This data report compiles ASPS Plastic Surgery Statistics into mean patient ages across 14 procedures, with full per-procedure tables and an interactive chart.",
        href: "/resources/plastic-surgery-patient-age",
      },
    ]}
  />
</div>

</Layout>
